      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": "https://uofa.net/morrison/activity/cfd-validation-run-opB-2024",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/morrison/data/experimental-hemolysis-benchmark"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/validation/rh-index-worst-case-comprehensive",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Comprehensive Worst-Case Hemolysis Validation — Full 5-Point Operating Envelope with Geometric Sensitivity",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/morrison/data/experimental-hemolysis-benchmark",
      "description": "This validation result captures the full five-point flow-speed operating envelope (2–5 L/min, 2500–4000 RPM) used to identify worst-case hemolysis conditions. Simulations were executed using the ANSYS Fluent 2022R2 solver with the Morrison power-law hemolysis model (C=1.8×10⁻⁶, α=1.9, β=0.765) on a 4.2 million element polyhedral mesh. Mesh independence was confirmed via Richardson extrapolation across three refinement levels (GCI < 2.1% for all QoIs). Boundary conditions were set to match the in vitro test loop conditions: phosphate-buffered saline with bovine blood at 37°C, inlet flow rates measured via Coriolis flowmeter (±0.5%), and rotational speed controlled by closed-loop tachometer feedback (±5 RPM). The relative hemolysis index RH was computed for each operating point against the predicate device experimental data collected at the Morrison Laboratory between March and August 2023. All five operating points yielded RH < 1.0 (range: 0.61–0.93), confirming the acceptance criterion. Geometric sensitivity runs across ±10% impeller tip clearance and ±5% volute width showed RH variation of less than 0.08, supporting robustness of the worst-case identification. The simulation campaign spanned approximately 14 weeks of compute time on a 256-core cluster, with results reviewed and signed off by two independent senior engineers prior to inclusion in this credibility package."
    }
  ],
